# Many-Model Forecasting on Databricks

Train one scikit-learn model per SKU (or any group key) and manage the full
lifecycle — training, hyperparameter optimization, model registry, and
inference — using Unity Catalog and MLflow on Databricks.

Instead of logging each SKU-level model as its own MLflow run (which causes
API rate limiting, redundant metadata, and an unusable experiment UI at
scale), both notebooks use the **pickle-bundle approach**: workers train
models and return serialized bytes as data, then a single MLflow pyfunc
model wraps the entire collection.

This project provides two approaches to the same problem so you can choose
the right tool for your scale:

| Notebook | Approach | Best for |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `multi-model-spark.py` | Spark `applyInPandas` | Simple per-group training, no HPO, fewer SKUs |
| `multi-model-ray.py` | Ray Data `map_groups` + Optuna HPO | HPO per group, 1000s+ SKUs, GPU models |

## Architecture

Both notebooks share the same overall flow: distribute training across
workers, collect pickled model bytes, bundle into one artifact, and log
a single MLflow run.  They differ in the execution engine and whether
HPO is performed.

### Spark Notebook

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  SparkDF["Spark DataFrame"] --> Repart["repartition(N, sku_id)"]
  Repart --> ApplyPd["groupby.applyInPandas()"]
  ApplyPd --> TrainSpark["Train RF per SKU\npickle.dumps(model)"]
  TrainSpark --> Delta["Delta Table\nsku_id | model_bytes | metrics"]
```

- Each Spark executor trains one SKU and returns pickled model bytes.
- No MLflow calls happen on workers — pure compute.
- No hyperparameter tuning — single `RandomForestRegressor` per SKU.

### Ray Notebook

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  SparkDF["Spark DataFrame"] --> FromSpark["ray.data.from_spark()"]
  FromSpark --> MapGroups["groupby.map_groups()"]
  MapGroups --> TrainRay["Optuna HPO per SKU\npickle.dumps(best_model)"]
  TrainRay --> Delta["Delta Table\nsku_id | model_bytes | metrics"]
```

- Each Ray worker runs Optuna HPO for one SKU and pickles the best model.
- No MLflow calls happen on workers — no credentials needed.
- Bayesian HPO (TPE sampler) explores the hyperparameter space.

### Post-Training: Bundle and Log

After training, both notebooks follow the same post-training flow on the
driver:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  Delta["Delta Table\nsku_id | model_bytes | feature_names | metrics"]
  Delta --> Collect["Collect to Pandas\nfilter status=success"]
  Collect --> Bundle["Build bundle dict\nsku_id -> model_bytes, feature_names"]
  Bundle --> Pickle["pickle.dump(bundle)\n→ UC Volume .pkl file"]
  Pickle --> PyfuncDef["Define MultiSkuModel\n(mlflow.pyfunc.PythonModel)"]
  PyfuncDef --> LogRun["Single MLflow run:\nlog_model + log_artifact(metrics.csv)\n+ log_metrics(averages)"]
  LogRun --> Register["mlflow.register_model()\n→ Unity Catalog"]
  Register --> Inference["Inference:\nmlflow.pyfunc.spark_udf()\nor load_model()"]
```

## Data Flow

### Spark Notebook

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  A["Spark DataFrame"] -->|"repartition(N, sku_id)"| B["Partitioned by sku_id"]
  B -->|"groupby.applyInPandas()"| C["Spark Executor"]

  subgraph sparkWorker [Per-SKU Spark Executor]
    C --> D[train_test_split]
    D --> E["Train RandomForest\n(n_estimators=50, n_jobs=-1)"]
    E --> F[Evaluate on validation set]
    F --> G["pickle.dumps(model)"]
  end

  G --> H["Return: sku_id, model_bytes,\nfeature_names, metrics"]
  H --> I["Delta Table"]
```

### Ray Notebook

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  A["Spark DataFrame"] -->|"ray.data.from_spark()"| B["Ray Dataset"]
  B -->|"groupby.map_groups()"| C["Ray Worker"]

  subgraph rayWorker [Per-SKU Ray Worker]
    C --> D[train_test_split]
    D --> E["Optuna study.optimize()"]

    subgraph hpoLoop [Optuna HPO Loop x N trials]
      E --> F["Train RandomForest\n(sampled hyperparams, n_jobs=-1)"]
      F --> G[Evaluate on validation set]
      G --> H{"Best RMSE?"}
      H -->|Yes| I[Update best model]
      H -->|No| E
    end

    I --> J["pickle.dumps(best_model)"]
  end

  J --> K["Return: sku_id, model_bytes,\nfeature_names, metrics, hyperparams"]
  K --> L["Delta Table"]
```

## Approach Comparison

| Dimension | Spark `applyInPandas` | Ray `map_groups` |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Scheduling overhead** | ~seconds per task | ~milliseconds per task |
| **Max practical groups** | 100s - 1000s | 1000s - 1M+ |
| **HPO integration** | Manual loop or Hyperopt | Optuna (Bayesian TPE) |
| **GPU support** | Limited (Spark GPU scheduling) | Native (`num_gpus` per task) |
| **Data transfer** | Arrow (Spark to Python) | Arrow (Spark to Ray, zero-copy) |
| **Autoscaling** | Databricks autoscale (node-level) | Ray autoscale (task-level) |
| **Infrastructure** | Spark cluster only | Spark + Ray (additional setup) |

Both notebooks use the pickle-bundle approach, so there is no per-SKU
MLflow overhead in either case.

**Rule of thumb:** Start with Spark `applyInPandas` for simplicity.  Move to
Ray when you need HPO per group, have 1000s+ groups, need GPU scheduling, or
hit Spark's per-task scheduling overhead.

## Configuration

Both notebooks use Databricks widgets for configurable parameters:

| Widget | Default | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `catalog_name` | `main` | Unity Catalog catalog for tables and models |
| `schema_name` | `forecasting` | Schema within the catalog |

### Setting via notebook UI

Widgets appear at the top of the notebook when you run it.  Type new values
and re-run the Configuration cell.

### Setting via job parameters

```python
dbutils.notebook.run("multi-model-spark", timeout_seconds=3600, arguments={
    "catalog_name": "prod",
    "schema_name": "ml_forecasting",
})
```

### Tables and models created

| Asset | Spark notebook | Ray notebook |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Models Delta table | `{catalog}.{schema}.sku_models` | `{catalog}.{schema}.sku_models_ray` |
| UC model | `{catalog}.{schema}.sku_model` | `{catalog}.{schema}.sku_model_ray` |
| Bundle artifact | `/Volumes/{catalog}/{schema}/model_artifacts/all_sku_models.pkl` | `/Volumes/{catalog}/{schema}/model_artifacts/all_sku_models_ray.pkl` |
| Metrics CSV | `/Volumes/{catalog}/{schema}/model_artifacts/sku_metrics.csv` | `/Volumes/{catalog}/{schema}/model_artifacts/sku_metrics_ray.csv` |

## Cluster Requirements

### Spark notebook (`multi-model-spark.py`)

- **Runtime:** DBR 15.4 LTS ML or later
- **Workers:** CPU instances (e.g. `m5.xlarge`, `i3.xlarge`)
- **Min nodes:** 1 driver + 1 worker (more workers = more parallel SKUs)
- No special Spark configs required

### Ray notebook (`multi-model-ray.py`)

- **Runtime:** DBR 15.4 LTS ML or later (includes Ray 2.x)
- **Workers:** CPU instances (e.g. `m5.xlarge`); for GPU models use `g4dn.xlarge`
- **Min nodes:** 1 driver + 2 workers (Ray on Spark requires multi-node)
- **Recommended Spark configs:**

  ```
  spark.task.resource.gpu.amount  0       # Reserve GPUs for Ray, not Spark
  RAY_memory_monitor_refresh_ms   0       # Avoid spurious OOM kills
  ```

## Usage

### 1. Import notebooks

Upload both `.py` files to your Databricks workspace (e.g.
`/Repos/<user>/multi-model/`).

### 2. Attach to a cluster

Use a cluster that meets the requirements above.  For the Ray notebook,
ensure it is a multi-node cluster.

### 3. Run the notebook

Run all cells top to bottom.  The notebooks will:

1. Create the catalog, schema, and UC Volume if they don't exist.
2. Generate synthetic training data (10 SKUs x 100 rows each).
3. Train one model per SKU, returning pickled bytes and metrics.
4. Write models + metrics to a Delta table.
5. Bundle all pickled models into a single `.pkl` artifact.
6. Log the bundle + metrics CSV as a single MLflow experiment run.
7. Register the pyfunc model in Unity Catalog.
8. Demonstrate distributed inference via `spark_udf` and single-node pandas.

### 4. Adapting for your data

Replace the synthetic data cell with a read from your feature table:

```python
df = spark.read.table("catalog.schema.sku_features")
```

Update `feature_cols` and `target_col` in the Configuration cell to match
your schema.

## Model Storage

### How models are stored

Unlike the traditional approach of one MLflow run per SKU, both notebooks
store models as pickle bytes in a Delta table and consolidate them into
a single bundle:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  subgraph training [Distributed Training]
    W1["Worker 1: SKU_001\npickle.dumps(model) → bytes"]
    W2["Worker 2: SKU_002\npickle.dumps(model) → bytes"]
    WN["Worker N: SKU_N\npickle.dumps(model) → bytes"]
  end

  subgraph delta [Delta Table]
    DT["sku_models\nsku_id | model_bytes | feature_names | rmse | ..."]
  end

  subgraph bundle [Pickle Bundle]
    PKL["all_sku_models.pkl\n{sku_id: {model_bytes, feature_names}}"]
  end

  subgraph mlflowRun [Single MLflow Run]
    Artifact["Artifacts:\n- model/ (pyfunc with bundle)\n- evaluations/sku_metrics.csv"]
    Metrics["Metrics: avg_rmse, avg_mse, avg_mae, num_skus"]
  end

  subgraph ucRegistry [Unity Catalog]
    UCModel["catalog.schema.sku_model\nVersion N"]
  end

  W1 --> DT
  W2 --> DT
  WN --> DT
  DT --> PKL
  PKL --> Artifact
  Artifact --> UCModel
```

### Why this is better at scale

| Concern | Per-SKU MLflow logging | Pickle bundle |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **MLflow runs created** | N (one per SKU) | 1 |
| **Artifact uploads** | N (each with env snapshot) | 1 |
| **API calls during training** | O(N) | 0 (workers don't call MLflow) |
| **Experiment UI** | N runs — slow, unnavigable | 1 run — clean |
| **Rate limiting risk** | High at 1000s+ SKUs | None |
| **Worker auth required** | Yes (credentials on workers) | No |
| **Inference loading** | Load N models from N runs | Load 1 bundle |

### MultiSkuModel pyfunc

The custom pyfunc class wraps the bundle:

- `load_context()` — opens the pickle bundle, deserializes all SKU models
  into an in-memory dict.
- `predict()` — routes each input row to the correct SKU model based on
  the `sku_id` column in the input DataFrame.

This means a single serving endpoint or `spark_udf` handles all SKUs.

## Inference

Both notebooks demonstrate two inference patterns:

### Distributed inference (Spark UDF)

```python
loaded_udf = mlflow.pyfunc.spark_udf(spark, model_uri=model_uri)
predictions_df = inference_df.withColumn(
    "prediction", loaded_udf(struct(*[col(c) for c in inference_df.columns]))
)
```

The pyfunc bundle is loaded once per Spark executor and applied in parallel
across the full DataFrame.  The `sku_id` column routes each row to the
correct internal model.

### Single-node inference (pandas)

```python
model = mlflow.pyfunc.load_model(model_uri)
predictions = model.predict(pd.DataFrame([
    {"sku_id": "SKU_001", "feat_1": 50.0, "feat_2": 25.0, "feat_3": 10.0},
]))
```

### Serving endpoint

Because the registered UC model is a standard pyfunc, it can be deployed
to a Databricks Model Serving endpoint.  A single endpoint serves all SKUs:

```python
from databricks.sdk import WorkspaceClient
w = WorkspaceClient()
w.serving_endpoints.create(
    name="sku-forecasting",
    config=EndpointCoreConfigInput(
        served_models=[ServedModelInput(
            model_name="catalog.schema.sku_model",
            model_version=model_version.version,
            workload_size="Small",
        )]
    ),
)
```
